                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d367">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">860C.002/12–2743: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Prime Minister</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Churchill</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to President <persName type="to"
                            >Roosevelt</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-27T18:37:00+01:00">27
                            December 1943—6:37 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>523. 1. I understand you have invited Polish Prime Minister to visit Washington,
                    arriving January 15. Would you very kindly consider <pb facs="0507" n="495"
                        xml:id="pg_495"/> whether this visit could not be postponed for a month or 6
                    weeks? This would enable me to see the Poles before they leave. If they come
                    over to you with no sort of agreement, is there not a danger of their becoming
                    the centre of Polish enthusiasm, much of which is likely to be anti-Russian and
                    may this not cost them dear? I am sure you will not mind my making this
                    suggestion.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
